<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100GMT, Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The ninth congress of Syria's ruling Arab Baath
Socialist Party opens here Saturday morning, during which Bashar
al-Assad, son of late Syrian President Hafez al-Assad, is expected
to be named the new leader of the party.
</P>
<P>
This means a further step for Bashar, 34, toward the presidency
of Syria.
</P>
<P>
Bashar will be elected secretary general of the party to replace
his father, who died on June 10 at the age of 69. (Syria-Baath-
Congress)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said here on Saturday
that the Palestinian people have been frustrated by the lack of
progress in their peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak during a meeting
that Israel is not moving in the final-status talks and fails to
make serious proposals on solving the thorniest issues of which
nothing has changed, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr said after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Arafat accused Israel of not being serious and not moving in any
of the main issues in the negotiations, including the final border
of a future independent Palestinian state, the status of Jerusalem,
Jewish settlements and the fate of Palestinian refugees, Moussa
told reporters. (Egypt-Palestine-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss Saturday sought
support from Arab countries in the United Nations in handling
verification of Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon, Lebanese
National News Agency (LNNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Hoss called Arab League Secretary-General Esmat Abdel-Meguid
Saturday and briefed him of the result of the border inspection
carried out jointly by teams of Lebanese and U.N. experts.
</P>
<P>
During his telephone conversation with Meguid, Hoss said Israel
still occupies Lebanese territory at some parts of the border and
several pieces of Lebanese lands are still under Israeli control.
(Lebanon-Israel-Verification)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA) leader Yasser
Arafat described his recent meeting with U.S. President Bill
Clinton as " very important and fundamental," expressing hope it
can lead to a trilateral Palestinian, U.S. and Israeli summit.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remarks after his return home from Egypt here
Saturday afternoon, expressing thanks to the U.S. side for the
efforts they made to revitalize the peace process on the
Palestinian track. (Arafat-Clinton-Summit) 
</P>
</TEXT>
