<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Kills MKO Members Plotting Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Islamic Revolution Guards
Corps (IRGC) on Sunday killed two members of the Iraq-based
military opposition Mujaheddin Khalq Organization (MKO) near the
border with Iraq, the official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to IRGC command headquarters, the two had tried to
infiltrate into Iran for sabotage via the border town of Qasre-e
Shirin in the western Kermanshah Province. They were killed in
armed clashes with IRGC personnel, IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The documents recovered from them indicated that they had
intended to bomb part of the city of Kermanshah, including the
headquarters of the provincial security force.
</P>
<P>
Large amount of ammunition, including hand grenades, and
communication sets, were seized from the infiltrators, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The MKO was a famous political-military group fighting against
the late Iranian shah's regime. It was outlawed in 1981 and fled to
Iraq following sharp differences with the clergy brought to power
in the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The group has since carried out numerous attacks against Iranian
targets both inside and outside Iran, causing casualties and
damage. Iran raided its bases in Iraq in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq, who fought a bloody war from 1980-88, still host
each other's oppositions, which is a major obstacle to a
normalization of relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
