<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief in Cairo for Talks on Issues Related to Lebanon, Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua ) -- United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan arrived in Cairo Sunday on the second leg of a Middle
East trip mainly aimed at ensuring Lebanon shall remain calm
following Israel's withdrawal from the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon arrival, Annan said there are some
problems over verification of Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon and
definition of the border, but both sides have agreed to solve the
issues in cooperation with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Israel completed troop withdrawal from a border strip in
southern Lebanon on May 24, ending 22 years of occupation there.
</P>
<P>
Annan on Friday confirmed Israel had fully withdrawn from
southern Lebanon under the U.N. Security Council Resolution 425.
But Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss disputed the confirmation,
insisting that Israel still occupies land in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Annan voiced confidence that the problems between Lebanon and
Israel will be solved soon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he stressed the importance of continuing the Mideast
peace process and expressed hope that the new Syrian leadership in
the making will work within the peace framework.
</P>
<P>
Following the death of Syrian President Hafez al-Assad on June
10, the country's ruling Baath Party has been working to promote
Bashar, son of the late president, to the supreme position.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived here after a visit to Iran. He will also travel to
Lebanon, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria and Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
