<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Hopes Cyprus Talks Not to Be Affected by Addendum Affair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. official Sunday expressed
hope that Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash's displeasure over
the dropping of an addendum from a resolution renewing UNFICYP's
(U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus) mandate will not not affect the
peace talks on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General's Special Advisor for Cyprus Alvaro de
Soto Sunday afternoon ended his four-day visit to the island, which
was overshadowed by ambiguous remarks of the Turkish Cypriots
regarding their participation in the third round of U.N.-sponsored
proximity talks, due to start on July 5 in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, de Soto stressed the process of the talks
may be interrupted only if the needs of the talks dictate so.
</P>
<P>
De Soto's visit to the island had been dogged by fury in the
north over the exclusion of the addendum to the renewal of the
UNFYCYP mandate, which would have given Turkish Cypriot permission
for the force's continued presence on the island.
</P>
<P>
The addendum was dropped on Wednesday after Cyprus' government
branded it as being tantamount to recognition of the Turkish
Cypriot regime and threatened to block the renewal unless it was
removed.
</P>
<P>
U.N. resolution 186, which ordered the U.N. peacekeeping force
to Cyprus in March 1964, said the U.N. consults with the government
of the Republic of Cyprus for the maintenance of the force on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Unhappy with the U.N. move, Denktash has announced he could not
rule out withdrawing from the proximity talks.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing the difficulties ahead, de Soto said "recent
developments have not necessarily improved the climate, " saying
Denktash told him he is considering his position in the light of
these developments.
</P>
<P>
Asked if there is a commitment by Denktash to go to Geneva, de
Soto replied, "I think Mr Denktash will be in Geneva, that is my
personal feeling."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus have been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island after a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the two sides on the Mediterranean island have
held two rounds of proximity talks under U.N. auspices in an effort
to prepare the ground for substantive talks which may lead to a
comprehensive settlement of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
De Soto left Sunday afternoon for Athens and Ankara.  
</P>
</TEXT>
