<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Stresses EU Role in Mideast Peace Making </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
on Sunday called on the European Union (EU) to play an important
role in bridging differences between Israel and its Arab neighbors
in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The monarch made the appeal when meeting with EU Middle East
peace envoy Mieguel Muratinos over the latest developments of
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks and on ways of achieving a just,
durable and comprehensive in the region, Jordan's official news
agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah described Israel's pullout from southern Lebanon in May
after over two decades of occupation as a "positive step" toward a
comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Israel's peace talks with Syria, a major power broker in
Lebanon, were deadlocked in January after the Jewish state rejected
a Syrian demand to give back in full the Golan Heights it captured
from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian track, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
resumed the final status peace talks in Washington earlier this
month but have failed so far to make substantial progress on issues
such as the status of Jerusalem, the return of Palestinian refugees
to their homeland, border demarkation and water sharing
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Muratinos expressed his appreciation for Jordan's
role as a major peace broker in the Arab-Israeli peace talks, and
pledged that the EU will continue to work for peace and stability
in the region, Petra said without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace agreement with Israel in 1994 as one of
the only two Arab countries after Egypt to strike such a peace deal
with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah and Muratinos also discussed cooperation between Jordan
and the 15-member EU, which provided some 100 million U.S. dollars
annually in various aid packages to the kingdom, the second largest
donor next to the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
