<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Total trade exchanges between Arab states and Israel
from January to September 1999 reached 91.091 million U.S dollars,
down 0.2 percent from 91.29 million during the same period the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
This was released by an official Egyptian economic organization,
which was regarded as the first to monitor Arab-Israeli trade.
</P>
<P>
It said Israel exported 61.21 million dollars worth of products
to the Arab countries while imported only 28.8 million worth of
goods from them.
</P>
<P>
Israel has trade relations with Egypt, Jordan, Morocco, United
Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Tunis, Oman, and Mauritania.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- Palestinian Planning and International Co-operation
Ministry said the program intended to create jobs in tourism,
commerce, industry, and agriculture sectors needs financial
assistance of about 696 million dollars from the donor countries.
</P>
<P>
The fund covers the requirements of employing 17,500 or 23
percent of the estimated 74,000 Palestinian jobless, the ministry
said in a paper submitted to the two-day Conference of the U.N.
Organizations which wrapped up in Gaza this week.
</P>
<P>
A top official with the ministry said that each single job
needed 6,000 to 10,000 dollars in the agricultural domain, 150,000
dollars in infrastructure, and 25,000 t0 30,000 dollars in
industry.
</P>
<P>
On Palestinian exports and imports, the official said 96 percent
of the Palestinian exports in 1998 headed for Israel, 2.3 percent
to Jordan and the remaining to other Arab and foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)-Saudi Arabia trade
committee will meet in Riyadh on June 24 to discuss obstacles
hindering the flow of trade between the two countries. The UAE side
will be led by Mohammed Ali bin Zayed, Acting Under Secretary at
Ministry of Finance and Industry for Industry.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Gulf Air will resume it seasonal flights from the
Gulf to Geneva next month, to cater to the tourists going to
Switzerland on summer vacations.
</P>
<P>
The twice-a-week-service will resume on July 1, operating from
Abu Dhabi on Wednesdays and Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
The airlines will operate its Airbus 330-200 on the route. "It
has become custom for Gulf Air to operate on the Gulf-Geneva route
during the summer months to absorb the demand on this sector at
this time of the year," said Dr. Sheikh Ahmed bin Saif Al Nahyan,
president and chief executive of Gulf Air. 
</P>
</TEXT>
