<HEADLINE> G-15 Summit to Seek Cooperation, Fairer World Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Group-15 countries
from Africa, Asia and Latin America began gathering here Sunday for
a summit aimed at seeking ways to enhance inter-group cooperation
and establish a fairer world order of international economy and
trade.
</P>
<P>
Among the arrivals were Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe,
Indonesian President Abdurahman Wahid, Argentine President Fernando
de la Rua of Argentina, Brazilian Vice President Marco Maciel and
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 members want an order for international economy and
trade less unjust, Maciel told reporters upon arrival in Cairo. The
group has formed this common ground, he said, adding that it will
also discuss economic globalization and its effects on the
developing world during the two-day summit due to open on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the G-15 wants a means of cooperation among developing
countries and also seek to create a mechanism of cooperation with
industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has already proposed the G-15 form a ministerial group
to represent them at the World Trade Organization in Geneva. The
group would keep in contact with international economic fora,
coordinate stands on world commerce and promote trade among G-15
states.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting Saturday evening, the G-15 foreign ministers
drafted a final summit declaration saying "the multilateral trade
system should function in a more open, more equitable and more
objective way."
</P>
<P>
The draft stressed the "need to take economic development into
consideration as a main dimension in multilateral trade
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The G-15 leaders are expected to discuss ways to draw private
investments for small- and medium-sized industries, relieve debt
and fight cheap imports undermining their domestic industries.
</P>
<P>
The G-15, founded in 1989, groups 17 nations -- Algeria,
Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Kenya, Jamaica,
Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Sri Lanka, Venezuela and
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
