<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moment of Truth for Palestinian Talks Approaches: Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
Sunday told his inner-circle security cabinet ministers that the
moment of truth for the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks is fast
approaching.
</P>
<P>
"We are reaching the end of a political corridor, which started
with the Oslo agreement, and the time has come for decisions to be
made," the prime minister said in a statement issued after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Barak said the talks with the Palestinians are dealing with the
core of conflicts between Israel and Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The subjects currently being discussed are complicated and
sensitive, the prime minister stated, adding how they will be
resolved will affect the lives for generations to come in the
region.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel is committed to reaching a settlement and is
ready to make difficult decisions while protecting its vital
interests, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Barak also suggested the Palestinians are foot-dragging the
peace process, saying it is impossible to force an agreement
without the good will of the Palestinian leadership.
</P>
<P>
The security cabinet meeting, which Barak termed as "one of the
most important meetings since the government was formed" in last
July, lasted more than five hours and will continue in the near
future, maybe on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The special meeting on the Israeli-Palestinian talks was
convened at the request of variable coalition factions. Some of
them had been complaining that Barak keeps them in dark about what
is happening in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The talks are aiming to reach a framework agreement and a final
accord by September to resolve their disputes over so-called final-
status issues, such as the fate of Jerusalem, the return of
Palestinian refugees, Jewish settlements, border, security and
water.
</P>
<P>
Barak asserted at Sunday's meeting that he prefers a
comprehensive framework agreement on the permanent settlement to a
partial agreement, which will leave some thorny issues to be ironed
out later.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of the talks between Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators has ended in Washington and the two delegations are
heading home on Sunday without making any tangible progress.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from Israel Defense Forces (IDF) general staff,
Military Intelligence and the Mossad Intelligence Agency Sunday
presented the security cabinet meeting with possible scenarios that
might arise with or without an Israeli-Palestinian framework
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The intelligence sources warned that if Israel does not reach a
deal with the Palestinians, there is a real risk of Palestinian
violence, even direct military confrontation between the IDF and
the Palestinian National Authority, according to Israel Radio
reports.
</P>
<P>
They argued Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat will have nothing
to lose from such a confrontation, in case that there is no peace
agreement with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
