<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea Sign Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia and Eritrea signed here on
Sunday morning a cease-fire deal to end their two-year-long border
dispute.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin and his Eritrean
counterpart Haile Woldetensae inked the accord at an official
ceremony attended by Algerian President and current chairman of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) AbdelAziz Bouteflika, OAU
Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim, U.S Presidential envoy Antony
Like, EU envoy to the Horn of African Region Renault Seri and
foreign ambassadors accredited in Algiers, Algerian News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, Bouteflika praised the deal as "a
historical event" which crowned the efforts made to restore peace
and stability in the Horn of Africa region.
</P>
<P>
The peace deal calls for an immediate truce and the deployment
of a U.N peacekeeping force in a 25-kilometer buffer zone in
Eritrea until the border between the two countries is demarcated.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea have been engaged in a long standing border
dispute since May 6, l998 when the Eritrean troops invaded and
seized some Ethiopian territories under sovereignty claims.
</P>
<P>
The renewed fighting between the two neighbor countries since
May 12 this year inflicted huge casualties and property losses on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
Indirect talks between Ethiopia and Eritrea proceeded here from
May 29 to June 10 under supervision of Algerian presidential envoy
on Ethiopian-Eritrean border dispute Ahmed Oyehiya.
</P>
<P>
On June l4, Addis Ababa formally agreed on the draft deal
already accepted by Eritrea on June 9.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord will pave the way for launching negotiations on
implementing the framework agreement on the Ethiopian-Eritrean
border dispute drafted by the OAU during the OAU Summit meeting in
Algiers in July l999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
