<DOCNO> XIE20000618.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portugal Makes Last-Ditch Attempt on Tax Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA MARIA DA FEIRA, Portugal, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Portugal,
that is hosting a two-day European Union summit, gave it a last go
on Sunday to forge an accord on cross-border savings taxation.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers of the 15 EU member states arrived a day
earlier than the heads of state and government for a special
council that was expected to forge an accord on how to levy tax on
cross-border savings.
</P>
<P>
The accord, once signed into law, will affect EU citizens of
the 15-nation bloc irrespective of where they live.
</P>
<P>
Yet the issue of taxes on non-resident savings accounts to
deter tax evasion has divided the 15 EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Britain was opposed to such an accord as it perceived a threat
to the lucrative eurobond market based in the City of London.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg was also opposed to the accord as it is also an
attraction to cross-border savings thanks to its low savings tax.
The country, like Austria, has a tradition of banking secrecy.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg and Austria were blocking the proposals that banking
information on bank accounts held by non-national residents be
exchanged to help solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
At the last EU finance minister council on June 6, Portugal,
that is holding the six-month rotating presidency of the 15-nation
bloc, suggested a compromise proposal.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese proposed a "coexistence" model by which EU
member states can opt for either direct taxes on cross-border
savings or exchange information on bank accounts held by non-
national residents. The model was proposed to exist indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
The issue of tax reformation has been hindering the internal
reforms of the European Union which is also trying to reform its
voting mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government are meeting in this town 40
kilometers south of the northern Portuguese city of Porto on June
19 and 20, to discuss a range of issues including internal reforms,
European defense and lifting the sanctions against Austria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
