<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Delays U.N. Council's Endorsement on Israeli Withdrawal From Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Sunday requested
the United Nations Security Council delay to endorse the
conclusion by the U.N.Secretary-General that Israel had withdrawn
its forces from Southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The request was made by Russian Envoy Vladimir Sergeev as the
Council was going to have a formal meeting to consider a
presidential statement on the subject.
</P>
<P>
"we would likely clarify before we take a decision. As far as
we know there is additional information which is directly related
to this item," Sergeev said.
</P>
<P>
British Envoy Stewart Eldon, who apparently got angry, said" I
would simply point out the matter we are currently considering is
urgent."
</P>
<P>
"We have already spent a long time considering it. We hope the
break will be short and we will be able to present this in a short
session," Eldon added.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. diplomats, the 15-member Security Council
had reached agreement on the presidential statement after 10 hours
of negotiations Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The statement calls on the Lebanese Government to ensure the
return of its effective authority and to maximize its presence in
the south.
</P>
<P>
It welcomes the measures taken by the Secretary-General to
beef up the 4,500 U.N. peacekeeping force in Lebanon, but it
stresses that the U.N. redeployment to the border should be
carried out in coordination with the redeployment of the Lebanese
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan announced Friday that Israel
had withdrawn its forces from Lebanon in accordance with
Resolution 425 of 1978.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanon on Friday and Saturday rejected Annan's
announcement, saying that Israeli forces are still on Lebanon's
soil.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and occupied part of southern
Lebanon as a buffer zone against guerrilla attacks. It announced
its withdrawal on may 24.  
</P>
</TEXT>
