<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schussel Criticizes Portugal for Lack of Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA MARIA DA FEIRA, Portugal, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The federal
chancellor of Austria on Sunday criticized Portugal for lack of
dialogue with his country on the issue of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Wolfgang Schussel, who arrived for the June 19-20 European
Union summit of heads of state and government, said after meeting
with European Christian Democrat leaders that Portugal, that is
holding the rotating presidency of the 15-nation bloc, should
communicate with its EU partner more.
</P>
<P>
"It is strange that there has been such communication with the
media and not directly with us," said the federal chancellor.
</P>
<P>
"By the end of the presidency, we want a proposal that will
mark the beginning of the end of sanctions, as until now there has
been nothing," he added.
</P>
<P>
Portugal is coming toward the end of its six-month presidency.
</P>
<P>
The southwestern European nation announced in January on behalf
of all the other EU member states a political sanction against
Austria just prior to the swear-in of its coalition government on
February 4.
</P>
<P>
Austria's EU partners threatened with and later applied
political boycotts and non-support for Austria's running for posts
in international institutions after Schussel's conservative People
's Party had reached an agreement with Joerg Haider's far-right
Freedom Party in forming the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Some EU member states including Finland and Italy are now keen
on finding a way out of the measures against Austria whereas
others including France and Belgium are still taking a hard-line
against Austria.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama visited Vienna last
Friday and acknowledged that Austria had done nothing "unorthodox"
in the European Union or domestic legislation.
</P>
<P>
Gama proposed that Austria adopt a gentler approach toward its
EU partners and a new analysis be made to decide whether to lift
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
But the Austrian chancellor rejected the Gama proposal of
putting Austria under observation as a prelude to lifting the
sanctions. He described the observation proposal without dialogue
as "animal experiments".
</P>
<P>
In a sign of conciliation, however, EU heads of state and
government have agreed to line up with Schussel for the usual
family photo during the two-day summit starting next Monday.
</P>
<P>
A few leaders had refused to appear in a family photo in March
when the previous EU summit was held. The then visiting Mexican
president had to join in to group the EU leaders for a photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
