<HEADLINE> Mubarak, U.S. Official Discuss Economic Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met
on Sunday with U.S. Secretary of Treasury Lawrence Summers to
review global, regional and local economic changes, Egyptian
Minister of Economy and Foreign Trade Youssef Boutros Ghali said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Summers tackled economic globalization and its
effect on developing countries, in addition to Egyptian-U.S.
economic and trade relations, said Ghali, who attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
They also touched on the role of the Group-15 in changing the
world views on the developing world, he added
</P>
<P>
The G-15 members from Africa, Asia and Latin America are
scheduled to open their two-day summit here on Monday to deal with
the world economic development trends and seek common stances as
well as inter-group cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Summers said the
Egyptian economy has experienced profound changes over the past 10
years, which gave the country potential for opportunities in
investment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called on Egypt to continue the privatization of
banks for the creation of more private banking.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official expressed hope that the two countries will
forge closer economic cooperation in the coming years, as Egypt
will be pursuing more private sector-oriented banking.
</P>
<P>
Egypt began the privatization process of bank in 1999 by selling
its shares in banks set up in cooperation with foreign partners. It
is to sell its shares in four such banks this year.
</P>
<P>
Summers arrived here Saturday at the start of his African tour,
which will also take him to Nigeria, Tanzania, South Africa and
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the second-largest recipient of U.S. aid after Israel.
The U.S. foreign aid budget for 2000 has set aside 735 million
dollars for Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
