<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Mahathir Discuss World Economy Prior to G-15 Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met
with Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad on Sunday to discuss
the world economic development and bilateral relations ahead of the
Group-15 summit beginning on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Egyptian Economy and
Foreign Trade Minister Youssef Boutros Ghali said the two leaders
dealt with the general international economic and financial issues,
and coordinated the two countries' positions during the two-day
summit.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Mahathir also tackled the policies adopted by
Malaysia when the Asian financial crisis erupted in the summer of
1998, Ghali said, adding that the Malaysian prime minister
expressed hope to benefit from Egypt's experience in economic
reform and privatization.
</P>
<P>
Egypt kicked off the economic reform program in 1991. The
process, considered as one of the most successful in the world, has
largely improved the country's macroeconomic situation and created
positive environment for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir arrived in Cairo on Saturday for the G-15 summit. He
has reportedly called for unity among developing nations to stand
up against what he said discriminatory policies set by developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 was founded in 1989 to enhance economic and trade
cooperation among developing nations. It has 17 member states,
namely Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia,
Kenya, Jamaica, Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Sri
Lanka, Venezuela and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
