<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Denies Rebels Place in Proposed Interim Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government said on
Sunday that there is no space for separatist Tamil Tiger rebels in
the proposed interim council for the war-torn North-East Province.
</P>
<P>
"Only those representatives of the registered Tamil, Muslim,
and Sinhala democratic political parties representing the North-
East should participate in the proposed Interim Council," a
government press release quoted President Kumaratunga as saying.
</P>
<P>
The release came as some organizations had made statements
alleging the government had agreed to establish an interim council
with the support of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
The release said the government's stand is that "the LTTE could
participate in an Interim Council only on entering the democratic
political mainstream by shunning all murderous terrorist
activities."
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting for a independent homeland
in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The government has banned LTTE, and branded it as a terrorist
organization that has been accused of plotting dozens of terrorist
bomb attacks in recent years against government officials,
security forces and economic targets.
</P>
<P>
The release said the government reached agreement with the main
opposition United National Party last week that referendum would
be the means of deciding whether the Northern and Eastern
Provinces should be merged as one province or should be separated.
</P>
<P>
It added that until the referendum is held, an interim council
would be established to administer the currently merged North-East
Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
