<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets On Israeli Withdrawal From Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18 (Xinhua -- The United Nations Security
Council was called into meeting Sunday to endorse the withdrawal
of Israeli forces from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council met on the same subject Saturday and it is
expected to work out a presidential statement today, which will
endorse the complete withdrawal of Israeli forces from Southern
Lebanon, thus paving the way for the United Nations to strengthen
its peacekeeping forces in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Council's move came after the announcement by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan Friday that Israeli forces had
completely withdrawn to their side of the border as stipulated
under a 1978 Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanon on Friday and Saturday rejected Annan's
announcement, saying Israeli forces are still on Lebanese soil.
</P>
<P>
The Council held long consultations Saturday on the
presidential statement but failed to reach agreement due to
divisions among them.
</P>
<P>
The Council was called into a formal meeting this morning but
it was suspended at the request of Russia, one of the five
permanent members.
</P>
<P>
Russia said it needed more time to consider the decision and
Security Council should continue consultations before the formal
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential statement calls on Lebanese Government to
ensure the return of its effective authority and to maximize its
presence in the south.
</P>
<P>
It welcomes measures taken by the Secretary-General to beef up
the 4,500 U.N. peacekeeping forces in Lebanon, but it stresses
that U.N. redployment to the border shall be carried out in
coordination with the redployment of the Lebanese armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and occupied part of southern
Lebanon as a buffer against guerrilla attacks on northern Israel
from 1985 until its withdrawal on May 24.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan will visit Lebanon Monday
and the Security Council is under pressure to endorse the Israeli
withdrawal from Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
