<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abundant Relics Unearthed from Turkey's Ancient Zeugma Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Plenty of artifacts have been
unearthed from southern Turkey's ancient Zeugma site which is
threatened to be flooded by a Dam, since the government ordered to
step up excavations.
</P>
<P>
Seven villas, 65,000 bullas, a bronze statue of Mars, small
channels, many statues, tap apparatus, animal and plant-decorated
water installation equipment, frescos, and 2,000 square metre
mosaics have been found at the site, a Roman Ruin in the southern
Gaziantep province.
</P>
<P>
Those artifacts will be displayed in the Culture Center which is
being constructed in the garden of Gaziantep Ancient Site, Anatolia
news agency reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Zeugma is called a "second Pompeii" by some archaeologists
because it shelters the unique bronze statue of war and fascinating
mosaics dating back to the Roman times.
</P>
<P>
Turkey quickened the pace of excavations as some parts of the
site will be subject to flooding by the Birecik Dam across the
Euphrates River, one of the government's ambitious plans to
generate electric power and irrigate vast areas of dry land.
</P>
<P>
The fate of the would-be-inundated site has drawn the attention
of high-level officials. Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit will
visit the site on June 20.
</P>
<P>
The ancient site was found by German archaeologist Jorg Wagner
in 1976 and systematic excavations were launched by the Gaziantep
Archeology Museum in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, the site of numerous ancient Greek and Roman cities,
boasts of antiquities that are among the finest and most abundant
in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
