<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Names New PM to Speed up Reforms 1st lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- In a step to spur economic reforms,
Jordanian King Abdullah on Sunday named leading parliamentarian Ali
Abu Ragheb as new prime minister to succeed Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh,
informed sources disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The lame duck prime minister was seen meeting with foreign
visitors Sunday morning, but Ali Abu Ragheb, 54, may take over as
early as Sunday evening, or at most in a couple of days, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Ragheb is expected to submit to King Abdullah the name list of
his new cabinet, comprising 27 to 29 ministers who are either known
as veteran politicians or young technocrats.
</P>
<P>
Ragheb, chairman of the financial and economic affairs committee
and two-time minister of industry and trade in 1991-93 and 1995,
has risen in the eyes of Abdullah for his efficiency in drawing a
master plan to develop the southern harbor city of Aqaba into the
kingdom's largest special economic zone.
</P>
<P>
The 38-year-old monarch was seen eager to carry out
understandings reached with the World Bank, the International
Monetary Fund and other major creditors to accelerate economic
development in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts believe Ragheb will help usher in a more
harmonious era between the government and the parliament,
particularly with the 80-member house of deputies or the lower
house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh, though widely seen as a conservative, has been at odds
with the house over political and economic policies, including its
crack-down upon muslim dissidents, the privatization of key but
non-profitable state enterprises, an introduction of a 10-percent
sales tax which triggered a price hike in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Ragheb, a U.S.-educated engineer, believes that parliamentarians
should be included in the government or cabinet, and he might
summon a few of his fellow house members into his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh has tided over several confidence crises during his 15-
month service as prime minister, including a rumor that his son was
asking for millions of U.S. dollars in bribes from potential
foreign investors to help them win construction contracts in the
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh managed to keep its job as the kingdom, which had
suffered a decade-old economic recession following the 1990 Gulf
Crisis, achieved a rare 1.5 percent economic growth in 1999 and is
eyeing for a three percent growth in 2000.
</P>
<P>
But his failure to win support from the house and a lack of
personal charisma is costing him his job now, as the 38-year-old
king expects harmony between the legislature and government as the
kingdom is heading for a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Ragheb, given his liberal economic background, is widely
expected to follow the economic and reform policies of Rawabdeh,
which were also endorsed by Abdullah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
