<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Calls for Observance of Palestinian Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei stressed here on Sunday the legitimate rights of the
Palestinian people must be observed in order to achieve peace in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The rights of the Palestinian nation cannot be ignored, nor can
the rights of several million Palestinian refugees be overlooked,
Khamenei said in a meeting with United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the U.N.'s effective part in settling the Middle East
dilemma, Khamenei also expressed his unhappiness with the multi-
standards the U.N. follows in resolving international issues due to
the dominance of certain powers.
</P>
<P>
"We are not satisfied with the stance of the U.N. and the
Security Council in helping resolve international issues because
the world body does not follow a single standard in dealing with
international issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the recent withdrawal of Israeli forces from South Lebanon,
the leader pointed out the Lebanon-Israel dispute "has not come to
an end", noting that Israel must withdraw from other Lebanese
lands, namely the Shebba Farms on Lebanon's border with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Iran supports the Lebanese people vindicating their rights and
the dispute between Lebanon and Israel should be resolved in a way
that all the Lebanese territory be handed over to Lebanon, Khamenei
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. secretary-general presented a report to Khamenei on the
withdrawal of Israeli forces from South Lebanon and the U.N.
activities on border demarcation.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the assistance of Iran and other regional
countries in helping resolve the Middle East issues.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived here Sunday within his week-long Middle East tour.
During the one-day visit, he also conferred with Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami and Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi on the latest
developments in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Annan has left Tehran for Cairo to continue his regional tour.
</P>
