<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Deregulate Furnace Oil Imports: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Finance Minister
Shaukat Aziz said Sunday the government has decided to deregulate
the furnace oil imports and the prices of Liquid Petroleum Gas (
LPG).
</P>
<P>
With this decision the private sector will be allowed to freely
import and distribute furnace oil, he said at the post-budget
press conference here.
</P>
<P>
He said the price of LPG will be deregulated from September
2000 with the commencement of production in the PARCO Refinery
that would add 450 tons of LPG to the existing supplies of 540
tons in the market.
</P>
<P>
With this development Pakistan might be in a position to export
LPG, as the expanded supplies would be more than the local demand,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister further said regulatory agencies namely the Gas
Regulatory Authority (GRA) and Petroleum Regulatory Board (PRB)
are being established to independently regulate the activities of
the oil and gas sector.
</P>
<P>
Presently, he said, huge amounts of foreign exchange are spent
on the import of furnace oil used for generating electricity at
power stations.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is making every effort to exploit the
country's natural gas potential so that the power stations can be
shifted from furnace oil to gas not only to save foreign exchange
but also to reduce the electricity tariff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
