<HEADLINE> Expanding Revenue Base Key Target of Budget 2000-2001: Shaukat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Finance Minister
Shaukat Aziz said on Sunday the primary focus of the newly issued
budget is towards expanding the revenue base to give sizable
allocation to the development sector and poverty reduction program.
</P>
<P>
"This budget mirrors direction of the government's economic
policy with major thrust on creating fiscal discipline and
ensuring stringent expenditure control," the minister added while
addressing a post-budget press conference here.
</P>
<P>
Shaukat Aziz said the budgetary proposals envisage a three-year
framework with clear-cut objectives to be realized at the end of
the third year.
</P>
<P>
This framework, he assured, would ensure consistency and
continuity in the economic policies and approach of the government
to achieve the specific targets for the ultimate revival of the
sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday night Shaukat issued the budget for 2000-2001, the
first by the current military government which assumed power last
October and has been ruled by the Supreme Court to hand over the
power to an elected government within three years.
</P>
<P>
Shaukat said significant effort was made in the budget to
reduce the fiscal deficit from 193.1 billion rupees (3.64 billion
U.S. dollars) or 6.1 percent of GDP to 162.1 billion rupees (3.06
billion dollars) or 4.6 percent of GDP during the next fiscal year
besides ensuring 24 percent increase in tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
The tax to GDP ratio is estimated to improve from 11 percent to
12.4 percent in the next fiscal which commences in July.
</P>
<P>
Increase in the current budgetary expenditures has been
restricted to two percent while development expenditures reflects
around 20 percent increase in the budget, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Special focus is put on poverty alleviation. Out of the 120.4
billion rupees (2.27 billion dollars) of Public Sector Development
Program, 21.2 billion rupees (0.4 billion dollars)is allocated to
poverty alleviation, against merely 3.5 billion rupees (0.07
billion dollars) in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
Spelling out specific targets of the three-year framework
carved in the budget, Shaukat said, GDP is estimated to grow at
six percent annually with inflation to be contained around four
percent by the end of the plan.
</P>
<P>
Investment to GDP ratio will increase to 18 percent and fiscal
deficit decline to 3.5 percent of GDP, he said, adding, current
account deficit will be brought down to about 0.5 per cent of GDP
from 2.4 percent during the year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange reserves will increase to nearly 12 weeks of
imports from the present level of 4 weeks of imports under the
three-year framework, he said.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question, the minister said Information Technology
is given immense concessions and tax incentives which would
provide a tremendous push to the development of this sector and
generate employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out possibility of any devaluation of Pakistani rupee,
adding that there is stability in the exchange rate, controlled by
supply and demand forces of the market.
</P>
<P>
The minister further said a comprehensive strategy was carved
by the Debt Management Committee to tackle the debt situation in
the country. The major objective of this exercise is to achieve
self reliance, he said.
</P>
<P>
He concluded the country would seek loans but only for the
development purposes on commercial basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
