<HEADLINE> U.S. Hails Agreement on Elimination of Child Labor in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 18 (Xinhua) - The United States welcomed the
agreement signed in Geneva on June 16 to continue the program to
eliminate child labor from Bangladesh's garment industry, a
special release of the U.S. Embassy in Dhaka said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Highly appreciating the 1995 Memorandum of Understanding MOU)
initiated by the Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and Exporters
Association (BGMEA), the International Labor Organization (ILO)
and the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), the special
release hoped the one-year extension of the agreement will promote
the progress.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will continue providing education and
rehabilitation assistance to the retrenched child workers and
facilitate the development of a new framework to ensure garment
factories free of child labor, the release said.
</P>
<P>
"The success of the 1995 MOU, the first agreement of its kind
in the world, should be attributed to the hard work and commitment
of the three parties of the MOU," the release said.
</P>
<P>
It said Bangladesh's garment manufacturers and exporters have
demonstrated that an industry can eliminate child labor
voluntarily and in a socially responsible way, and this effort can
contribute to booming production and exports by reducing the
concern of buyers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
The United States is pleased to assist in the success of the
1995 MOU through contributions totaling 1.7 million U.S. dollars
from the U.S. Department of Labor, almost all of which went to the
ILO-managed factory monitoring program, said the release.
</P>
<P>
"The United States looks forward to continuing this
participation under the new agreement in the next year." 
</P>
</TEXT>
