<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Capital Remains Calm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Somali capital city of
Mogadishu is calm despite its hosting of several warlords opposing
to the Djibouti peace conference now continuing its second and
last face for the establishment of a government for the country.
</P>
<P>
It is now quite normal in every corner of Mogadishu to hear
every now and then the thunderous double explosions of the
anti-aircraft rockets being tested in the air by the militiamen of
the faction leaders.
</P>
<P>
The warlords are not just quiet, but seem to be preparing
themselves for the worst to happen when their current ostensible
international isolation turns into real segregation from the rest
of the leaders in terms of their constituency and influence in
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Every morning since the Djibouti peace conference began 47 days
ago, the people in Mogadishu had their morning tea over talks of
the achievements the meeting has made in the past 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
And Sunday's discussion was how the delegates have miraculously
and courageously chosen Hassan Abshir Farah (Mogadishu's former
governor from Puntland) and Abdalle Derow from the Rahanwein
Resistance Army as the two co-chairmen of the conference.
</P>
<P>
Both men have left behind the wild political desires of their
leaders Colonel Abdullahi Yussuf (President of Puntland regional
government) and Colonel Hassan Shargudud, chairman of the RRA.
</P>
<P>
The Djibouti conference has revived the long ago dead hopes for
the restoration of Somalia's nationhood, said Muhidin Trabune, a
famous whole salesman in Mogadishu's main business center, Bakara
market.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Abdi Ali, a businessman on the Bakara market, believed
that the warlords won't just sit down idly. It all depends upon
the power the provisional government is equipped with, he said.
</P>
<P>
This will make the warlords either to flee for their lives or
dare fight the government, he added.
</P>
<P>
Other businessmen held that the warlords are now being left
with no other alternative, but to fight.
</P>
<P>
The current regrouping of the warlords shows their intention of
 stimulating their closest subclans to fight using all possible
militiamen in an attempt of spreading the war into the entire
clans and the subsequent chaos would destroy any government, said
Farah Aliyow Aw-Ahmed, another businessman in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
President Ismail Omar Ghelleh of Djibouti proposed the
three-point plan in regard to the faction leaders.
</P>
<P>
First, they will officially be invited to attend the
conference.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, if they refuse to accept the invitation, their assets
outside the country will be frozen and their movements abroad the
country will be limited.
</P>
<P>
And third, if the first two don't force them to join the peace
process, a special court will be set up for their indictment to
war crimes during the civil wars in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Abdi Mohamed, a businessman and a politician, said that
the three- point plan will be another factor forcing the warlords
to fight.
</P>
<P>
Once the provisional government comes into Mogadishu, Hussein
Aidid, Mohamed Qanyare, Osman Atto and Muse Sudi Yalahow will be
the first to challenge it, Mohamed added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
