<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Welcomes Ethiopia-Eritrea Cease-fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Sunday expressed
satisfaction with the signing of a cease-fire agreement between
Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
"The sides have taken a step to laying the foundation for the
transition of the settlement of existing territorial differences
to a solely peaceful channel," the Russian Foreign Ministry said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin and his Eritrean
counterpart, Haile Woldensae, inked the accord in an official
ceremony in Algiers, Algeria, earlier Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We highly appreciate the statesmanship and the understanding
of the futility of the military solution to the problem that has
been demonstrated in both capitals," the Russian Foreign Ministry
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The next item on the agenda "is a speedy signing by the sides
of other fundamental settlement documents and their consequent
practical implementation," the Interfax news agency quoted the
statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are firmly convinced that only such a course of
developments meets the vital interests of Eritrea and Ethiopia and
also the Horn of Africa as a whole. Russia as a U.N. Security
Council permanent member is ready to continue to give all-round
assistance to the peace process," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire agreement calls for an immediate cessation of
hostilities between the two sides and the deployment of a U.N.
peacekeeping force in a 25-kilometer buffer zone until the
disputed border is demarcated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
