<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Secluded Grottoes to Open to Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DUNHUANG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Yunlin Grottoes, a major yet
secluded part of the renowned Dunhuang Caves in the northwest
China province of Gansu, are expected to open to visitors soon.
</P>
<P>
With a five-year consolidation project costing over seven
million yuan nearing its end, the grottoes are expected to first
open to visitors as part of a series of activities to be held to
mark the 100th anniversary of the discovery of the Sutras Cave at
Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the resplendent and magnificent frescoes in the
Mogao Grottoes, the murals in the Yulin Grottoes are simple and
elegant. Different in general tone as they are, the two groups of
grottoes are closely related in carving, fresco content and
artistic style, said Wang Wanfu, a deputy director in charge of
preservation work at the Dunhuang Research Academy.
</P>
<P>
"The Yulin and Dunhuang grottoes complement each other
perfectly as representatives of Dunhuang culture," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Located in a desert ravine, the Yulin Grottoes are home to 41
caves featuring exquisite frescoes covering more than 1,000 sq m
and over 1,000 Buddhist statues.
</P>
<P>
Cave 25 is said to be the most exquisite of the Yunlin Grottoes,
with frescoes depicting scenes of everyday life during different
historical periods, including the Tang Dynasty, Five Dynasties,
Song Dynasty and Yuan Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Liangfu, an expert on Dunhuang studies, said the
frescoes in Cave 25 are the best-preserved of all the grottoes of
Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
The intact nature of the frescoes is mainly attributable to the
special geological location of the grottoes and government
protection measures, said Li Zuixiong, vice-president of the
Dunhuang Research Academy. The first road to the Yulin Grottoes
was built in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Yulin Grottoes were listed as a cultural heritage site
under first-class state protection in 1961. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
