<HEADLINE> Iran's New Parliament Reviews Press Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran's newly inaugurated sixth
Majlis (parliament) on Sunday approved a motion to review the press
law which was amended by the conservative dominated fifth Majlis in
April.
</P>
<P>
In an open session presided over by speaker Mehdi Karrubi, the
new parliament approved the motion submitted by 106 parliament
members, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Amendments to the press law by the conservative fifth parliament
has, in recent months, triggered a mass suspension of 17 reformist
papers and periodicals and led to the imprisonment of a number of
reformist journalists on charges they "disparaged Islam and the
ideals of the Islamic revolution."
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Bourqani, a parliament member from Tehran and a main
architect of the motion, said the suspension of the mass-circulated
periodicals is similar to the closure of schools in society.
</P>
<P>
If a thought is not allowed to emerge, it will lead to dogmatism
which is a big threat, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another parliament member from Tehran, Seyed Hadi Khamenei, also
said the approval of the amendments to the press law by the fifth
parliament was "a move taken hurriedly."
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that a proper solution would be find to the
issue so as to ease press challenges and anxieties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a total of 151 members of the newly convened
parliament have written a letter to head of the judiciary Mahmoud
Hashemi Shahroudi, demanding an urgent action to ease the
restrictive press law, IRNA reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"...the incorrect action of the Tehran justice department
against the press in recent months has not only diminished its
reputation in the public mind but is an affront to the nation," the
letter read in part.
</P>
<P>
It termed the imprisonment of journalists as an "insensible"
action and called for serious considerations in this respect.
</P>
<P>
The new parliament, which started functioning on May 27, is
dominated by reformists supporting moderate policies of President
Mohammad Khatami. 
</P>
</TEXT>
