<HEADLINE> Pakistan Not to Enter Arms Race: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan will not enter arms
race with any country and will instead follow a peaceful path of
socio-economic development, said Finance Minister Shaukat Aziz in
his post-budget press conference here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said this when asked why Pakistan has not substantially
raised its defense expenditure while its neighbor has done so
considerably.
</P>
<P>
In the government's opinion the country must have a credible
defense, which is important for peace, the minister said, but
adding that the armed forces' requirements to protect the country
has been provided in the budget 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
"We want to defend our homeland and also move towards the goal
of socio-economic development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shaukat said the defense expenditure has in fact been increased
by 10 percent in the new budget, which is sufficient to meet the
defense requirements.
</P>
<P>
He also appreciated the defense establishment for using the
budget "very efficiently."
</P>
<P>
In its new budget issued Saturday night, Pakistan projected the
defense expenditure at 133.5 billion rupees (2.52 billion U.S.
dollars), 6.9 percent lower as compared with the previous year's
143.3 billion rupees (2.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the decrease was achieved as the expenditure on
military pensions was shifted to the general administration for
the first time in the history of the country, thus 26.1 billion
rupees (0.49 billion dollars) for all practical purposes was not
mentioned in the actual defense budget. 
</P>
