<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea Sign Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia and Eritrea signed here on
Sunday morning a cease fire deal to end their 2-year-long border
dispute, according to Algerian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin and his Eritrean
counterpart Haile Woldensae inked the accord in an official
ceremony attended by Algerian president and current Organization of
African Unity (OAU) Chairman AbdelAziz Bouteflika, OAU Secretary
General Salim Ahmed Salim, U.S. Presidential envoy Anthony Lake, EU
envoy to the Horn of African Region Rino Seri and foreign
ambassadors in Algiers, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, Bouteflika praised the deal as "a
historical event" which crowned the efforts made to restore peace
and stability in the Horn of Africa Region.
</P>
<P>
The peace deal calls for an immediate truce and the deployment
of a U.N. peace keeping force in a 25-kilometer buffer zone in
Eritrea until the border between the two countries is demarcated.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea have been engaged in a border dispute since
May 6, l998 when the Eritrean troops invaded and seized some
Ethiopian territories of dispute. The renewed fighting between the
two neighbors since May 12 this year left huge casualties and
property losses on both sides.
</P>
<P>
Indirect talks between Ethiopia and Eritrea were held here from
May 29 to June 10 under supervision of Algerian presidential envoy
on Ethiopian-Eritrean border dispute Ahmed Oyehiya. On June l4,
Addis Ababa formally agreed on the draft deal already accepted by
Eritrea on June 9.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord will pave the way for launching negotiations on
implementing the framework agreement on the Ethiopian-Eritrean
border dispute drafted by the OAU during its Summit meeting in
Algiers in July l999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
