<HEADLINE> Indian Steel Giant to Cut Workforce in Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The SAIL, which now produces 10 million tons of steel a year,
will start a fresh round of voluntary retirement in the next two
to three months, the PTI quoted company chairman Arvind Pande as
saying in Calcutta.
</P>
<P>
According to the corporate plan prepared by the company, Bokaro
Steel Plant, which now has a 43,000-strong workforce, would have
30,000 employees by 2004, Pande told the PTI.
</P>
<P>
About 19,000 employees had already opted for voluntary
retirement in SAIL in the last two years, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that in the current financial year, the company's
loss is expected to be curtailed by 50 percent over those incurred
in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
The SAIL incurred a loss of 1.82 billion rupees (42.3 million U.
S. dollars) during the April-May period this year against 4.19
billion rupees (97.4 million U.S. dollars) during the
corresponding period last year, said the PTI. 
