<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Ranks First in World Traffic Accidents: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia, plagued by poor road
 conditions and congested streets, has ranked the first in the
world in traffic accident, the Fortune weekly reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia loses more than 12 million birr (about 1.45 million
U.S. dollars) annually due to traffic accidents, Mesfin
Bantayehu, a road expert in the capital city of Addis Ababa, was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 to 1998, over 28,000 accidents occurred in the
capital, five of which involved death, 25 percent caused light
injuries and 90 percent caused property damage, he said.
</P>
<P>
These accidents were probably connected with traffic congestion
in the city.
</P>
<P>
Mesfin said about 77 percent of the country's nearly 80,000
vehicles are in Addis Ababa, 91 percent of public vehicles and 95
percent of all trucks are in the metropolis.
</P>
<P>
According to Mesfin, there are 9,443 taxis, 335 city buses and
38,244 private vehicles in the capital, 1,360 trucks and 240
buses enter the city daily.
</P>
<P>
In addition to vehicles, non-motorized transport also adds to
the capital's traffic woes. There are nearly 5,000 donkeys in
Addis Ababa, and on market days, over 3,000 additional donkeys
enter the city, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mesfin expressed the belief that one of the solution to traffic
problems is to have more traffic police. However, the number of
traffic police throughout the country is decreasing from 478 in
1993 to 451 in 1999, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
