<HEADLINE> Thai Fast-food Chain Challenges Int'l Giants by Yang Qingchuan, Huang Yong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 18 (Xinhua) - To challenge the domination of
international fast-food giants of the Thai market, the Charoen
Pokphand (CP) Group, a top company here, has managed to set up and
rapidly expand Thailand's own fast-food business during last 12
years, CP vice president Adirek Sripratak said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"In the late 1980s, seeing that the western fast-food brands
flooding into the local fast-food market, we felt it is urgent to
set up Thailand's own fast-food business," Adirek stressed to
Xinhua during an interview.
</P>
<P>
"Our motive was to show to those international giants that we
can be a challenger to them," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he recalled, the situation at the beginning was not
rosy as those big foreign fast-food chain stores had already set
their footing in Thailand. In 1988, the CP Group initiated
Thailand's first fast-food chain: the Chester's.
</P>
<P>
Three famous international fast-food companies from the United
States --the Kentucky Fried Chickens (KFC), Mcdonald's and Pizza
Hut -- entered the Thai market in 1983, 1985 and 1975 respectively,
and the Chester's was naturally a less experienced newcomer.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, in terms of capital, technology and marketing
skill, the new Thai fast-food chain was obviously no match for
those big businesses.
</P>
<P>
"The situation was not so nice but we still had the confidence,
because we knew our own advantages," Adirek said.
</P>
<P>
"Our fast-food chain gets firm support from the CP Group, which
is the country's biggest producer of chickens, and we understand
Thai consumers' tastes better than foreign rivals," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Those advantages, he said, combined with advanced management,
unique food style, improved service quality, would lead to success
in the fierce competition.
</P>
<P>
"The Chester's expansion history can best illustrate the point,
" he stated.
</P>
<P>
During the past 12 years, the Chester's has successfully
expanded its business by setting up more that 60 branches all over
the country. Now it enjoys a 10-strong percent market share, and
co-dominates the Thai market with the three giants.
</P>
<P>
Considering the competitive cruelty within the Thai fast-food
market during the recent decade, the Chester's behavior is
impressive, as even some foreign giants, with strong capital and
technological backing, can hardly secure their survival or
development, Adirek noted.
</P>
<P>
There have been nearly a dozen foreign competitors failing or
disappearing from Thailand's fast-food market, namely the Popeyes,
A&AMP;W, BigBoy, ArBy's, Wendy's, Lona Jones Silver, Dairy Queen,
Shery's Pizza and Domino Pizza.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the factors for the chain's success, the senior
executive replied the first is "to be realistic."
</P>
<P>
"In other words, when we design our fast-food strategy, we
should put the whole market into account, comparing the advantages
and disadvantages between ourselves and foreign contenders, to
make our plan pragmatic," he remarked.
</P>
<P>
"We do not expect our fast-food store to 'become a billionaire
overnight', and prefer to go step by step, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Holding a place of number four in terms of market share, the
Chester's now anchors its goal to become number three or number
two in the future, Adirek remarked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
