<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hutton Fails to Beat Free Diving Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- South African diver Trevor Hutton
Saturday failed to break the world free diving record at Cyprus'
southwestern Limassol coast, local media reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
To break the world record, currently held by Moroccan Pierre
Frolla, Hutton had to pass the 72-meter mark on official attempt
days, June 16, 17 and 18.
</P>
<P>
During the dive, Hutton managed to reach the mark, but he
blacked out six meters from the surface on the return.
</P>
<P>
He recovered immediately but decided to scrap Sunday's attempts.
</P>
<P>
Hutton, 29, and his 30-member support team had been practising
for the 72-meter dive since last week.
</P>
<P>
A depth difficult enough for the most experienced and well-
equipped scuba diver, free divers descend on a single breath of
air with no breathing apparatus.
</P>
<P>
And in Hutton's category of free apnea, the diver plunges to
depths without the help of fins or weights and only a rope to pull
himself up and down.
</P>
<P>
Hutton, who had managed to equal the record during one of the
practice sessions, said he was thinking of trying again in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
