<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- An aqua fantasy park was officially opened in Selcuk,
south of Izmir, on Saturday to add a new attracting site to the
Aegean coastal tourist route in southwest Turkey, reported Turkish
Daily News on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The park, one of Turkey's largest water parks, costs 17 million
U.S. dollars and has numerous special entertainment sections
including a castle, pirate ship, 35 different water slides and
Turkey's first artificial river.
</P>
<P>
A holiday village with a 400-bed capacity will be established in
the park area next year.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey has officially promoted eco-tourism, not only
as a source of revenue, but also as an encouragement of eco-
conservation, reported Turkish Daily News on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, rich in eco-tourism resources, has hundreds of species
of birds, thousands of species of flowers including unique
varieties.
</P>
<P>
The British company Green Tours has been selling eco-holidays --
especially the bird-, plant- and butterfly-watching holidays -- in
Turkey for six years. Each year, they send two groups to the Lake
District, the maze of marshes, pastures and mountains north of
Antalya, a Mediterranean port city in south Turkey.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak places research
and development at the top of his economic priorities and favors
increasing the R&AMP;D budget, says an official in the Prime Minister's
office.
</P>
<P>
Barak is expected to address revisions of the law governing
state subsidies for corporate research on development at a
government meeting on Sunday. He will endorse the government
support but instruct the Finance MInistry and the Ministry for
Industry and Trade to work out details.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A plan for developing a joint Web site to promote
tourism to Egypt and Israel will be presented Monday to teams from
both countries at a meeting at the Egyptian resort city of Sharm el
Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
There are currently 92,000 hotel rooms in Egypt and the number
is expected to more than double within the next five years.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Tel Aviv, Jerusalem, Haifa and other
cities have drawn tens of millions of dollars from the pockets of
developers with illegal "parking ransoms", as shown by recent
decisions of government planning and construction appeals boards.
</P>
<P>
In a decision handed down two weeks ago, a regional board
invalidated the Jerusalem municipality's demand that, as a
condition for obtaining a construction permit, a developer must pay
a fee in lieu of putting in parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem municipality charges a 20,000 U.S. dollar parking
ransom for each parking space specified by building regulations. In
large projects, the fees may exceed one million shekels (about 250,
000 dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
