<HEADLINE> U.S. Hearings on Zimbabwe Dismissed by Latter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean Ministry of Foreign
Affairs has dismissed the congressional hearings on Zimbabwe being
held in the United States as a ploy to interfere in its internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government, which recently denied reports that it was
working in cahoots with the British Labor government to topple the
Mugabe government, last week started the hearings where former
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker called on his
country to join hands with Britain to dislodge the current
Zimbabwean government from power, the Sunday Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Zimbabwe
Saturday told the newspaper whereas any country could discuss its
relations with another country, it was wrong for institutions of
governments which subscribe to the U.N. Charter to entertain
schemes to subvert democratic processes in the territory of a
fellow member of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Attempts to tinker with the political process in
Zimbabwe to produce a result preferred by certain elements in the
United States and elsewhere constitute a violation of principles
of the United Nations Charter, and negate the very principle of
democracy itself."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said from its perspective, Zimbabwe's
relationship with the U.S. was by and large a good one. He
pointed out that the two governments sometimes agreed and at other
times differed in both experience and perspective.
</P>
<P>
However, what he found to be abominable were subversive
elements that he said were on "a malicious campaign of
misinformation and the creation of surrogates."
</P>
<P>
At the hearing, allegations were levelled against the
Zimbabwean government for perceived perpetration of violence
against members of the opposition, ignoring the rule of law and
jeopardizing democracy.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that Zimbabwe was in fact upholding
the rule of law, with the police arresting and prosecuting
perpetrators of political violence without regard to political
affiliation.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe and cabinet ministers have denounced such violence and
allowed international observers to observe the forthcoming
parliamentary elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
