<HEADLINE> Israel's Coalition Crisis Nearing Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel's coalition crisis with
Shas party is nearing solution as Shas representatives and One
Israel negotiators have reached agreements on almost all of the
disputed issues, Israel Radio reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Ehud Barak has provided more time for
the two sides to reach an agreement on resolving the coalition
crisis by postponing Sunday's cabinet meeting to Tuesday, at which
Shas was announced to submit the resignation of its ministers and
deputy ministers.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held another round of marathon meeting Saturday
night in Tel Aviv, which dealt with "how to implement the reform
plan for the Shas education network.
</P>
<P>
Progress has been made on the bailing out Shas' school network,
but the problem of legalizing a Shas' radio network remained, a
senior One Israel official told the radio.
</P>
<P>
The problem on the Shas radio network remains as it still
demands that its stations be included in a new network that would
be created for this purpose, while One Israel argued that legally
it would have to be included in the existing Second Radio and
Television Authority.
</P>
<P>
Shas has demanded millions of shekels to bail out its debet-
ridden school network and its pirate radio stations be legalized,
as conditions for not withdrawing from the coalition and not
supporting the opposition bill asking for early elections of the
Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
The supervision of Shas education network is the remaining
problem for the two sides, as Shas strongly insisted this
supervision will not be given to Education Ministry headed by Yossi
sarid.
</P>
<P>
Sarid, who is leader of the Meretz party strongly opposing to
allocate more education funds to Shas, refused to attend the
Saturday night meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meretz has said it will not agree to the appointment of
committee headed by Barak to supervise the Shas educational
network.
</P>
<P>
Shas Council of Sages decided on Tuesday that its cabinet
ministers would submit their resignations to Barak during the "next
cabinet meeting" which is scheduled to be held on Sunday, putting
Barak in a coalition dilemma since assuming the office last July.
</P>
<P>
The next few days will be crucial for Barak who has to find ways
to solve this crisis in one way or another. 
</P>
