<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has agreed to
give Tanzania credits worth 212 million U.S. dollars to enhance
its social- economic development, local newspapers reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the World Bank, quoted by the newspapers, said
that the credits are aimed at helping the government to reduce
poverty by building the assets of the poor, improving
infrastructure development and sustainable rural development.
</P>
<P>
Some 190 million U.S. dollars of the money would be issued as a
 programmatic structural adjustment credit and would be directed
towards boosting privatization and improving the business climate
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Another 22 million U.S. dollars would be issued under a health
sector development program and it would cover the first phase of a
12-year program designed to improve access to quality health
services especially for women and children.
</P>
<P>
"These objectives support the government's strategies outlined
in the Tanzania Assistance Strategy (TAS) and the upcoming Poverty
Reduction Strategy Paper (PRSP)," the statement said. 
