<HEADLINE> Cyprus Airways Earn Less Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus Airways (CY), the
national carrier, earned less profit in 1999 than that of 1998, the
local Sunday Mail newspaper reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1999 annual report of the Cyprus Airways, the
profit fell from 10 million pounds (16 million dollars) in 1998 to
8.8 million pounds (14.1 million dollars) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
in 1999 the airline had 25.2 percent of incoming and outgoing
air traffic on the island, whereas in 1998 its share was 27.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
Eurocyprian, CY's sister company, also lost ground slightly,
bringing its share of all scheduled and chartered flights down by
3.2 percent to 31.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Eurocyprian managed a pre-tax profit of 2.2 million Cyprus
pounds (3.5 million U.S. dollars) in 1998, but clocked up only 1.3
million pounds (2.1 million dollars) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The revenue earned from both charter and scheduled passenger
fell by 1.7 percent, from 93.6 million pounds (149.8 million
dollars) in 1998 to 92 million pounds (147.2 million dollars) in
1999.
</P>
<P>
The main factor to the profit margin was the huge hike in
operating costs, from 117.1 million pounds (187.4 million dollars)
in 1998 to 127.4 million pounds (203.9 million dollars) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Cy staff costs, the company's biggest outlay, also increased
because of the 3.6 percent rise in the cost of living and a one
percent pay increase.
</P>
<P>
But there were some areas of company growth. Income from freight
and mail increased by 7.6 percent, up to 8.5 million pounds (13.6
million dollars) from a 7.9 million pounds (12.4 million dollars)
in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
