<HEADLINE> Drought Drives Elephants Into Farms in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The protracted drought has forced
several elephants to invade farms around a village in coastal
Kenya, the Herald newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The invading of the elephants has caused fear and panic, which
 prevented the residents at Mitangani Location of Bamba Division
in Kilifi District from attending their farms, the paper quoted
the area councillor Coun Menza as saying.
</P>
<P>
Menza Saturday urged the Kenya Wildlife Service to come to the
residents' rescue and drive the animals back to the national park,
adding that these wild animals have been terrorizing the residents
since last year.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, a herdsman in northern Kenya was stoned to
death by monkeys in a scramble for a water hole between his
cattle and the monkeys.
</P>
<P>
The lingering drought has also put 22 million Kenyans, about 80
percent of the country's population, at the verge of starvation.
</P>
</TEXT>
