<DOCNO> XIE20000618.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's First Cloned Goat Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The world's first goat which was
cloned from adult body cells, died of breathing failure caused by
defects in lung development early this morning after living 36
hours and three minutes.
</P>
<P>
The goat, named "Yuanyuan," was found breathing with difficulty
yesterday when scientists were conducting normal health checkup
for the goat.
</P>
<P>
Scientists concluded that the breathing difficulty of the
cloned goat was caused by abnormal lung development.
</P>
<P>
Professor Zhang Yong from the Northwest University of Science
and Technology for Agriculture and Forestry, which cloned the goat,
said the death of "Yuanyuan" is normal, citing the high death rate
of all the cloned animals in the world.
</P>
<P>
"This means that the cloning technology leaves much room for
improvement," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000618.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman Expects to Enter WTO in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Oman expects to become a full
member of the World Trade Organization (WTO) in November, Sunday's
Dubai-based daily Gulf News quoted an Oman's Commerce Ministry
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The working party report and the protocols of (Oman's )
membership will be adopted (by the WTO) on July 6," said Al Riyami,
who is heading Oman's WTO negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
Oman has launched several reforms in its bid for full WTO
membership, including lifting fees levied by import agents on
imported goods.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf state has also taken steps to reduce restrictions on
foreign investment. Foreigners will be allowed to own 70 percent of
a local business from January 2001 compared to the current limit of

49 percent.
</P>
<P>
Oman will also allow 100 percent foreign ownership in some
financial services like banking, insurance and brokerages from
January 2003, and is intensifying its crackdown on copyright
piracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
