<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China's northernmost province of
Heilongjiang is seeking more opportunities in foreign economic
trade and cooperation, from Russia, in particular, this year, said
Wang Zhenchuan, vice-governor in charge of foreign economic and
trade affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Business Weekly, Wang welcomed foreign
investors during the ongoing 11th China Harbin Economic and Trade
Fair which runs through next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 enterprises from 50 countries and regions have
come to Harbin, the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
As one of the seven largest trade fairs in China, the annual
fair has become a significant stage for the province to
demonstrate its capabilities and to learn from others.
</P>
<P>
During the past ten years, more than 40 billion U.S. dollars in
transactions have been completed at the fairs.
</P>
<P>
The province has a 3,040 km borderline with Russia.
</P>
<P>
"We need more means of production from Russia while they need
means of subsistence and we obtain mutual benefit through
cooperation," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that by the end of 1999, trade volume
with Russia soared to 920 million U.S. dollars, up 35 percent on a
year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
"We will strengthen our cooperation with Russia in terms of
high and new technologies this year," Wang added. 
