<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's High Steel Prices Begin to Bend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua)-- Prices of steel products on the
Chinese market have begun to dip.
</P>
<P>
According to sources with the State Administration of
Metallurgical Industry, the average price of steel products has
declined by seven percent to eight percent, China Daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In coastal Shanghai, China's largest economic powerhouse,
prices of steel products for building materials dropped to about 2,
500 yuan (301 U.S. dollars) per ton from nearly 3,000 yuan (361 U.
S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
Prices of steel products have substantially increased since mid-
April thanks to the steel sector's resolute efforts to control
steel output.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of the year, the average price of
steel products increased by 80 yuan (9.6 U.S. dollars) from the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Prices of low-grade steel products exceeded 3,000 yuan per ton
in some areas.
</P>
<P>
Exorbitant prices will undermine the sector's efforts to
control output and close down small steel plants and will restrain
demand for steel products.
</P>
<P>
The steel sector plans to slash output by ten percent and shut
down more than 100 small steel plants across the country to
achieve a profit of ten billion yuan this year.
</P>
<P>
The sector's profits slid to 2.5 billion yuan (301 million U.S.
dollars) last year from a record high of 29.4 billion yuan (3.5
billion U.S. dollars) in 1993 because of low prices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
