<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladeshi Opposition Lawmakers to Return Parliament  by Pan Xiaozhu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- In a significant turn, lawmakers of
the four-party opposition alliance will join the current session
of parliament to retain their membership.
</P>
<P>
Chiefs of the opposition alliance made the decision at an
emergency meeting held in the capital on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina Saturday called upon opposition
leader Begum Khaleda Zia to return to parliament "not only to save
her membership but also to perform her duty to the people who
voted in her favor."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a big public meeting at Joypurhat, 280 kilometers
northwest of Dhaka, the prime minister said that she had a report
that the opposition MPs would return to the House only to retain
their membership in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
"Come to the House and join discussion, let's try to run the
parliament properly," she said.
</P>
<P>
As the opposition continued to boycott parliament sessions,
Chairperson of the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) and Leader
of the Opposition in Parliament Khaleda Zia and her allies in the
Jatiya Party, Jammat-e-Islami and Islami Oikya Jote (Islami
Solidarity Front) were absent from parliament for more than 60
days as of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As per the constitution if any member of parliament refrained
from attending the House for 90 consecutive days, his or her
membership would automatically be vacated.
</P>
<P>
If the opposition finally goes back to parliament, it will mark
a significant development in the course of politics of the country.
But whether the return will be tactical and what strategy the
opposition adopts is still unclear.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Manna Bhuiyan, secretary general of the BNP, told newsmen
Saturday night that the meeting decided to "foil a play of the
government to get the seats of opposition MPs vacated." "We will
not allow them to implement their design," he said.
</P>
<P>
President of Jatiya Party HM Ershad said that the opposition
would not allow the government to amend the constitution to suit
its purpose by taking advantage of the absence of their MPs from
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a big public meeting in the capital, Khaleda Zia
again accused the government for "harassing opposition activists."
</P>
<P>
She claimed that a nationalist government would be formed after
the next general elections as the people will reject the ruling
Awami League (People's League) for its failure and misrule.
</P>
