<HEADLINE> NATO-led Kosovo Force Commander Visits Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Huan Ortunjo, commander of the NATO-
led Kosovo Force, visited Macedonia Saturday to discuss matters on
reinforcing security along the border between Macedonia and the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo, said reliable sources in the
Macedonian capital of Skoplie.
</P>
<P>
Commander Ortunjo said he has discussed with President Boris
Trajkovski detailed measures to be adopted to effectively put the
border under control, although he did not reveal any details of
the measures.
</P>
<P>
He believed there exists a huge potential for the NATO-led
Kosovo Force and Macedonian border guards to increase their
cooperation in border security.
</P>
<P>
In a letter on June 6 to NATO secretary general George
Robertson, Trajkovski pointed out incidents and illegal crossings
have occurred one after another along the border with Kosovo in
the last few months. He strongly called on the NATO-led Kosovo
Force to adopt necessary measures to reinforce security along the
border.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonian government announced last week its border guards
would open fire without prior warning at persons crossing
illegally.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that two Macedonian border guards were wounded
on June 5 by sniper fire from inside Kosovo. It was the second
incident in two months. In early April, a group of Kosovo
Albanians kidnapped four Macedonian border guards, although they
were released later. 
</P>
