<HEADLINE> Russia, Moldova Prepares for Bilateral Fundamental Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Moldova are
accelerating their work for signing a bilateral fundamental treaty
as early as possible, visiting Russian President Vladimir Putin
said in Chisinau Saturday, a report from Moldova's capital city
said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries had no difference in principle on signing
such a treaty, stressed Putin, who is there for a 17-hour visit,
the last leg of his European trip.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with his Moldovan
counterpart Petru Luchinschi, Putin said Russia attaches great
importance to its ties with Moldova, considering it a foundation
for Russia's diplomatic activities in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The president also promised to take a more active approach on
withdrawing its 2,600 troops from the Russian-speaking region on
the eastern bank of the Dnestr River, which broke away from the
Romanian-speaking Moldova in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Russia will set up a special committee led by former Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov to solve the problem, he added.
</P>
<P>
At the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (
OSCE) conference in Istanbul last autumn, Russia pledged to pull
out all its forces by the end of 2002, but so far little progress
has been made.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Luchinschi said the two sides reached agreements
on the majority of issues in politics and economy at this summit,
while deciding to promote bilateral cooperation in global affairs
and in international organizations.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped Putin's visit will effectively push forward the
development of Russian-Moldovan relations, which has been hampered
by the Dnestr issue and Chisinau's huge gas debt of 800 million U.
S. dollars to Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
