<HEADLINE> Changchun to Dismantle Chimneys For Better Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Changchun, capital city of
northeast China's Jilin Province, this year plans to dismantle
more than 100 chimneys used for industrial production and heating,
thus reducing smoke and dust emissions by nearly 9,000 tons every
year.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say the move will also help reduce sulfur
dioxide emissions by 3,000 tons annually.
</P>
<P>
To curb the growing air pollution in the city, one of the
leading industrial bases in China, central heating systems will
gradually phase out small and polluting chimneys. The Changchun
city government will also tighten control over exhaust emissions
from vehicles. 
