<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Meets on Israeli Withdrawal From Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Annan's announcement cleared the way for the 4,500-member
United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon to be strengthened and
deployed in the border area.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanon on Friday and Saturday rejected the announcement
from Annan that Israel has now complied with a 1978 Security
Council resolution and withdrawn its troops, insisting that
Israeli forces are still on Lebanese soil.
</P>
<P>
The Council, after hours of meeting, is still debating on a
presidential statement which calls on the Lebanese Government to
ensure the return of its effective authority and to maximize its
presence in the south.
</P>
<P>
The presidential statement also welcomes measures taken by the
Secretary-General to beef up the United Nations Peacekeeping force
in Lebanon, and it stresses that U.N. redeployment to the border
shall be carried out in coordination with the redeployment of the
Lebanese armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The Council is expected to trim down its original statement on
what U.N. peacekeepers should do about their deployment in Lebanon
until Lebanon accepts the temporary border.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and occupied part of southern
Lebanon as a buffer zone against guerrilla attacks. It announced
its withdrawal on May 24 and U.N. cartographers marked out a
boundary based on maps made in 1923.
</P>
<P>
Annan will visit Lebanon Monday and the Security Council is
under pressure to endorse the Israeli withdrawal immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
