<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hackers Attack AOL Computer Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A spokesman for the company said that hackers compromised AOL
customer service representatives with e-mails containing a "Trojan
horse" attachment, which, when opened, created a connection to the
sender's computer and allowed access to some AOL accounts.
</P>
<P>
Hackers pilfered information such as names, addresses and
credit-card numbers from some subscribers, the company said. But
it declined to disclose the amount of victims, saying only "a very
limited" number of the records of the company's 23 million
subscribers had been accessed.
</P>
<P>
The software virus attack appeared to be similar in kind, but
by no means in scale, to the "ILoeveYou" virus that paralyzed tens
of millions of computers last month, penetrating networks in
government and companies worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The attack was deadly, however, said Mark Chen, chief
technology officer at Palo Alto, a California-based Securify
company.
</P>
<P>
"Since once someone gets through the security perimeter, he has
the access to all the powers of a person on the inside," Chen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
