<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Regional News In China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIAONING: Liaoning province, China's traditional heavy
industrial base, has begun to play a leading role in the country's
urbanization, according to local sources. The province has thirty-
one large, medium, and small-sized cities, with an urban
population of 16.45 million, accounting for 40 percent of the
province's total.
</P>
<P>
The Shenyang Municipal Government of Liaoning Province plans to
hold an international show on tour de force of 23 occupations,
including lathe work, benchwork, electric welding, hair-cutting,
ikebana and even patrol police, from August 15 to 22. It will be
the first time for Shenyang to hold such an event, which is
expected to help improve the skill of employees of all circles.
</P>
<P>
CHONGQING: The government of Chongqing Municipality, southwest
China, has decided to make tourism a pillar industry in the coming
ten years. In line with the city's long-term development program
issued recently, Chongqing's income from tourism industry will
reach 50.2 billion yuan by 2010, or 14 percent of the city's gross
domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
XINJIANG: The first expressway in northwest Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region is expected to open to traffic on October 1 this
year. The 265.51-kilometer-long expressway, which connects the
regional capital Urumqi with Kuytun city, runs through the
northern part of Xinjiang where the region's economic development
belt is located.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000618.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Regional News In China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI: The No. 2 subway line in Shanghai opened to traffic
on June 11. Costing a total of 12.3 billion yuan (about 1.5
billion U.S. dollars), the new 16.3-km line runs through west-east
Shanghai. The line is equipped with advanced facilities such as
special lifts for the handicapped, guiding facilities for the
blind, and toilets at the subway entrance.
</P>
<P>
A local court in Shanghai sentenced two copyright infringers to
two years and one and half years imprisonment on June 14 as they
were found guilty of stealing film copies of Shanghai Urban
Traffic Map. This is the first case of copyright infringement
involving criminal sentence in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
SICHUAN: The largest sewage disposal plant in western China was
put into use recently in Chengdu, the capital of southwestern
Sichuan Province. Construction of the plant, which is capable of
handling 300,000 cubic meters of waste water a day, or 40 percent
of the city's total, began three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan International Hospital, the first of its kind in
southwest China, was established in Chengdu, capital of the
province, on June 14. The hospital aims to provide better medical
care for foreign friends, overseas Chinese and compatriots from
Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan. Doctors, nurses and other employees
of the hospital can speak English, Japanese, German, or French.
</P>
<P>
GANSU: China is to build a museum to display the cultural
relics found in the world-famous "Sutras Cave" of Mogao Grotto in
Dunhuang, northwest China's Gansu province. The museum, scheduled
for opening in July, will be built on the former residence of
Taoist Wang Yuanlu, who found the Cave by chance about 100 years
ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
