<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese universities and colleges will enroll over two million
freshmen this year, according to an official from the State
Development Planning Commission on June 13.
</P>
<P>
To further reform higher education, the State Council has asked
provincial governments to give estimated enrollments for local
vocational colleges, the official said, adding that this means
provincial governments have more rights on regulating enrollments.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Planning Commission allocated nearly four
billion yuan (about 499 million U.S. dollars) of State bonds
annually for two years to improve college facilities.
</P>
<P>
Prestigious University Opens "Master Lectures"
</P>
<P>
The prestigious China University of Science and Technology in
east China's Anhui Province recently set up "master lectures" to
attract more first-class scholars and scientists to give lectures
to students.
</P>
<P>
The "master lectures" are named after famous Chinese scientists
or noted professors and scholars in Chinese scientific
establishment including Hua Luogeng, Yan Jici and Qian Xuesen.
</P>
<P>
 Universities Urged to Nurture Young Academics
</P>
<P>
China needs to train more young academics, said Chen Zhili,
minister of Education on June 15, at an awarding ceremony for 100
excellent young university teachers.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that China has awarded 100 young excellent university
teachers annually from last year, providing them with better
working and researching facilities to nurture a generation of
young leading scientists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
