<HEADLINE> Kuwait Holds no Iraqi POWs: DM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Defense Minister Sheikh
Salem al-Sabah Saturday claimed his country holds no Iraqi
prisoners of war (POWs) or political prisoners in its jails.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah, also head of the national committee for Kuwaiti POWs
and missing in action (MIAs), made the remarks in response to
earlier reports that Iraq has formed a committee to search for
Iraqi prisoners in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"We did not have any prisoners. Our jails are open before the
representatives of the International Committee of the Red Cross,
who pay frequent visits to Kuwaiti jails," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
"We held no (Iraqi) political prisoners, either," the Kuwaiti
News Agency quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated claims by the Kuwaiti government for the return of
the properties looted by Iraqi troops during their invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad accuses Kuwait of failing to provide information about
1,150 Iraqis who went missing during the 1991 Gulf War crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has repeatedly accused Iraq of continuing to hold 605
Kuwaitis and other nationals whom it detained during the seven-
month occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The prisoner issue has been a major stumbling block in the way
of normalization of Kuwaiti-Iraqi ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
