<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Seeks Interpol Arrest of $19 Million Swindler </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has sought
assistance from the International Police (Interpol) for the arrest
of a Dar es Salaam businessman suspected to be involved in an over
15 billion Tanzanian shillings (18.8 million U.S. dollars) case.
</P>
<P>
The Director of Criminal Investigation (DCI) Adadi Rajabu told
local media on Saturday that said Riyaz Gulamani, who fled the
country in September 1999, committed fraud and money laundering
affecting many financial institutions and individuals.
</P>
<P>
The DCI said that Riyaz Gulamani was holding a Tanzanian
passport. Adadi explained that Tanzanian police decided to seek
Interpol's assistance after it had established that Gulamani was
spending a lot of time in Canada.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that it was rather difficult to have Gulamani
out of Canada because Tanzania and Canada do not have extradition
protocol in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000618.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Urges for Communal Spirit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's President Olusegun
Obasanjo Saturday urged his countrymen to develop a communal
spirit, irrespective of where they come from and which kind of
belief they have.
</P>
<P>
"All hands must be on deck, and Nigeria should be on the agenda
of public debate, public discourse and public interest. It is the
only way to rebuild and reconstruct Nigeria," said the president
in a nationwide broadcast speech.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 people have been killed in various religious
and ethnic clashes since Obasanjo came to office in May 1999,
ending 15 years of military rule.
</P>
<P>
The country's three major nationalities, Yoruba, Igbo, and
Hausa have often been seen on a collision cause for more resources
and government positions.
</P>
<P>
"There must be a sense of sacrifice from everyone, of course
some will make more sacrifices than others, it is only then that
we can remove mutual suspicion," Obasanjo said.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time in three days that Obasanjo addressed
the nation after a crippling general strike over gasoline prices
threatened the political fabric of Africa's most populous nation,
which recently celebrated one year of democracy.
</P>
<P>
He also made the speech when the country's northern Kano and
Kaduna states had announced intentions to introduce the Islamic
legal system Sharia in their states again, which if materialized,
is almost certain to giver rise to new riots.
</P>
<P>
Kano and Kaduna are two most popular and influential states in
the northern part of the west African nation. Unlike other
northern states dominated by Muslim population, both of the two
states have a large Christian population.
</P>
<P>
Two northern states, Zamfara and Sokoto, have already
introduced Sharia into their criminal code earlier in the year,
despite the opposition from the Christian dominated southern
states and the federal government.
</P>
<P>
Sharia, mainly implemented in Islamic countries, is a code of
living for Muslims. Apart from its religious contents, the code is
known for its regulations that women must cover themselves, and
different sexes must be segregated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
