<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 149 Fans Arrested in Charleroi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Riot police clashed with English
and German fans Saturday in the Belgian small town of Charleroi as
tensions rose before the Euro 2000 match between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A total of 149 supporters, mostly English, were arrested by
the time the match began, accroding to reports.
</P>
<P>
Around 3,500 Belgian police were on patrol but they were
unable to prevent mass fighting as the groups of German and
English fans gathered in bars before the match, which England won
1-0.
</P>
<P>
Riot police used water cannon on two separate occasions in an
effort to prevent pitched battles between the fans, who were
massed on opposite sides of the main Charles II square.
</P>
<P>
But immediately after the match, the atmosphere was better-
natured as celebrating England fans sang in fountains in the
centre of Charleroi, but riot police kept a close watch.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before 1700 GMT, most of the arrested fans were being
held in cells and 20 were being immediately expelled from Belgium,
the Charleroi mayor Jacques Van Gompel and police chief Michel
Rompen told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Twenty of those arrested were found to be in possession of
illegal weapons, Rompen said.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said one English fan would appear before
magistrates next week on charges of striking a police officer.
</P>
<P>
Also being held was the chief of a local group of supporters
known as the "Wallon Boys."
</P>
<P>
A young woman was reported to have broken her leg, apparently
during the police charge in a bid to restore order.
</P>
<P>
The incidents in the afternoon followed similar outbreaks of
violence in Charleroi overnight which left an English fan in
intensive care after suffering cuts to his back.
</P>
<P>
British authorities were struggling Saturday to make
arrangements for the repatriation from Belgium of hundreds of fans
after a computer glitch brought air traffic to a halt.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian authorities were trying to fly back 343 fans
arrested on Friday during trouble in Brussels.  
</P>
