<HEADLINE> Peacekeepers Called for to Bolster Ethiopian-Eritrean Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
said here Sunday that U.N. peacekeeping forces should be
immediately deployed in an effort to bolster a peace deal signed on
Sunday between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The concerned parties should try to implement the peace
agreement quickly, Annan said of the accord that the two countries
clinched in Algiers, capital of Algeria, earlier to end their two-
year border war.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief arrived here Sunday during a multi-leg Middle
East tour. He told a news conference after meeting with Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa that the U.N. Security Council would
decide on a request for peacekeepers contained in the deal brokered
by the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been asked to send peacekeepers to the border area
of Ethiopia and Eritrea as well as to demarcate the border, he
said, adding that on this issue, both sides have reportedly agreed
to respect the U.N. demarcation.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed hope that U.N. member states will be willing and
prepared to provide troops and resources necessary for the task.
</P>
<P>
The peace deal calls for an immediate truce and the deployment
of U.N. peacekeeping forces in a 25-kilometer buffer zone in
Eritrea until the border between the two countries is demarcated.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea have been engaged in a border dispute since
May 6, l998 when the Eritrean troops invaded and seized some
Ethiopian territories. Fighting renewed last May along their 1,000-
kilometer border, with Ethiopian troops marching into Eritrea,
beyond disputed border regions which were at the root of the border
war.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moussa welcomed the ceasefire accord as an "important
step" towards making peace between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt is confident that the agreement would bring peace,
stability and security to the Horn of Africa, protect the two
African peoples and open the door to socio-economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
