<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Urges Majlis to Address Economic Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei on Sunday urged the Majlis (parliament) to pass
legislations on resolving economic problems.
</P>
<P>
The Majlis is expected to give priority to easing the economic
hardships and working to remove poverty in the society, Khamenei
said in a meeting with members of the new parliament.
</P>
<P>
The supreme authority of the islamic republic, staying above
factional rifts, seemed trying to persuade the victorious
reformists to focus on economic issues, rather than on political
struggle with the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The sixth parliament should pay attention to the economic
difficulties of the people, fight corruption, misuse of public
fund, and discrimination, and remove administrative and judicial
shortcomings, Khamenei said.
</P>
<P>
High inflation and unemployment are the two major economic
problems facing Iran.
</P>
<P>
The new parliament, dominated by allies of moderate President
Mohammad Khatami, started work on May 27. It approved a motion on
Sunday to ease the press law to resume banned newspaper and release
jailed journalists.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen reformist papers and journals were closed and a number
of reformist journalists and activists imprisoned in the fierce
struggle between the reformists and conservatives during the
parliament elections.
</P>
<P>
The reformists came out the winner in the elections. But as they
won their seats mainly on slogans of promoting political and
cultural freedoms, they seem not ready to address economic
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
