<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Pays Tribute to Outgoing PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
on Sunday named prominent legislator Ali Abu Ragheb as prime
minister to succeed Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh, but commended the latter
for his 15 months of service as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Ragheb is expected to be sworn in as prime minister before the
king in the coming days, most probably on Monday, informed sources
said.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Rawabdeh, King Abdullah praised him and his
cabinet members for working diligently and faithfully for the
country in the face of challenges and offering the country a lot of
accomplishments to be remembered with gratitude and appreciation.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Rawabdeh, in his letter of resignation, attributed
achievements of his government to the leadership of the 38-year-old
king, and praised the king for a "first, biggest and most important
role in all what has been accomplished in a relatively short period
of time".
</P>
<P>
The kingdom is expected to achieve a 3 percent economic growth
in 2000 after a 1.5 percent growth in 1999, apparently emerging
from a decade-old recession since the 1990 Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh was the first prime minister appointed in March 1999 by
King Abdullah who acceded to the throne a month earlier after his
father King Hussein Ibn Talal died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
The monarch has the constitutional power to appoint or dismiss
governments.
</P>
<P>
The decision by Abdullah to appoint Ragheb, 54, as the new prime
minister was apparently aimed at speeding up economic reforms based
on understandings with the World Bank, the International Monetary
Fund and other major international creditors, and to forge a more
harmonious relationship between the government and the legislature.
Rawabdeh, though known as conservative, had taken liberal measures
to reduce the deficits in state budgets, to pravitize key but non-
profitable state enterprises and to reduce public expenditures and
to attract more foreign investors into the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
But he was also attacked by liberals and conservatives alike for
alleged nepotism in appointments to senior jobs and for abuses of
public funds. He was also attacked by a rumor that his son had
asked for millions of U.S. dollars from potential investors.
</P>
<P>
He had been at odds with the parliament, particularly with the
80-member lower house, and failed to win support from the house for
some of his reforms partly due to a lack of personal charisma.
</P>
<P>
Ragheb, a parliamentarian since 1993 and two-time minister of
industry and trade, is expected to inherit and accelerate
Rawabdeh's reform packages, but possibly with more blessings from
the parliament given his background in the house.
</P>
<P>
He is heading the financial and economic affairs committee of
the house before being appointed prime minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
