<HEADLINE> Urgent: Security Council Endorses Israeli Withdrawal From Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council on Sunday endorsed the conclusion by U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan that Israel had withdrawn its forces from
southern Lebanon in accordance with Resolution 425 of 1978.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000618.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Endorses Israeli Withdrawal From Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18(Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council on Sunday endorsed the conclusion by U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan that Israel had withdrawn its forces from
southern Lebanon in accordance with resolution 425 of 1978.
</P>
<P>
The move came after two-day debate among the 15-member Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Annan reported to the Security Council Friday that Israel had
completely withdrawn its forces from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential statement, the Security Council welcomed the
steps already taken by the parties concerned to implement the
recommendations contained in the Secretary-General's report of May
22, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council calls on all parties to continue to
cooperate fully with the United Nations and the United Nations
Interim Force in Lebanon(UNIFIL) and to exercise utmost restraint.
</P>
<P>
The Council reemphasized the need for strict respect for the
territorial integrity, sovereignty and political independence of
Lebanon within its internationally recognized boundaries.
</P>
<P>
The Council urged the Government of Lebanese to ensure the
return of its effective authority and presence in the south and to
proceed with the deployment of the Lebanese armed forces as soon
as possible, with the assistance of UNIFIL, into the Lebanese
territory recently vacated by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Council stressed that the redeployment of UNIFIL should be
conducted in coordination with the Government of Lebanon and with
the Lebanese armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The Council looked forward to the completion of the mandate of
UNIFIL and will review by July 31, 2000, the need to extend the
present mandate of UNIFIL, taking into account the report of the
Secretary-General on the implementation of resolution 425 of 1978
and 426 of 1978.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and occupied part of southern
Lebanon as a buffer zone against guerrilla attacks. It announced
it withdrew on May 24 and U.N. cartographers marked out a
boundary based on 1923 maps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
