<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Airport Flights Gradually Return to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Flights at most UK airports were
gradually returning to normal on Sunday, as airlines fought with
the congestion caused by the collapse of the main air traffic
control computer.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of travellers were left stranded on Saturday, with
some forced to sleep overnight at airports.
</P>
<P>
The problem with the National Air Traffic Services (NATS)
computer, which handles all aircraft entering UK airspace, was
fixed by Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
But the backlog means that flight delays look likely to
continue for the rest of the day, although cancellations are down
to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
The busy airports of Heathrow and Gatwick have been hardest hit.
British Airways had to cancel 18 Sunday morning flights to
domestic and European destinations from Heathrow Airport.
</P>
<P>
This followed more than 80 cancellations on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Terminal manager at London's Gatwick Airport, Anthony Merlyn,
said no flights had been cancelled but most passengers could still
expect a delay of three to four hours as the backlog is cleared.
</P>
<P>
Manchester airport was also struggling to get back to normal
after the technical problems.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the airport said: "Passengers flying
transatlantic have not been affected but flights which crossed
Heathrow airspace were badly delayed yesterday."
</P>
<P>
The airports in Belfast and Glasgow were also affected.
</P>
<P>
NATS has promised a "thorough investigation" into the computer
breakdown, the second time the system has failed in a week.
</P>
<P>
The problem meant that flight course information, normally
passed electronically, had to be retrieved by hand.
</P>
<P>
The computer which failed should provide controllers with the
call sign of an aircraft, where it came from and its destination.
However, after it went down controllers still had radar and radio
control of aircraft.
</P>
<P>
All major British airports were affected as the controllers
were forced for the second time this month to resort to a manual
system to give instructions to planes in the air.
</P>
<P>
Engineers managed to bring the computer back on line by early
afternoon on Saturday, but after a breakdown lasting more than
five hours the congestion built up with planes badly delayed or
diverted from their destinations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
